# Phase 0 / Phase 1: local server uses SQLite, one file on disk.
DATABASE_URL="file:./dev.db"

# Phase 4 adds a second connection string for the VPS deployment
# (PostgreSQL) — not used by the local server at all. This is the VPS
# process's OWN .env, never the restaurant PC's.
#
# The actual deployment (docs/deployment-setup.md's "VPS server deployment"
# section) self-hosts Postgres via Docker directly on the VPS rather than
# using Supabase — a plain local connection to that container, not exposed
# beyond 127.0.0.1 on the VPS itself:
# DATABASE_URL="postgresql://cafeali:PASSWORD@127.0.0.1:5432/cafeali"
#
# If you'd rather use Supabase's managed Postgres instead, use its POOLED
# connection string (Project Settings → Database, port 6543 with
# `?pgbouncer=true`) — the VPS Fastify process, like any long-lived Node app,
# can open more connections than Supabase's small-tier direct-connection
# (port 5432) limit allows:
# DATABASE_URL="postgresql://postgres.xxxx:PASSWORD@aws-0-region.pooler.supabase.com:6543/postgres?pgbouncer=true&connection_limit=1"

# Shared secret the local server signs its service JWT with, and the VPS
# verifies with — distinct from JWT_SECRET (staff sessions). Generate a real
# random value for production, e.g. `openssl rand -hex 32`.
# VPS_SYNC_SECRET="change-me"

# Port the VPS Fastify instance listens on (host is always 0.0.0.0 — see
# src/vps/server.ts). 443 in the real deployment — required to be one of
# Meta's permitted webhook ports (443/80/88/8443) once the WhatsApp webhook
# is in play (see below), not just an arbitrary choice.
# VPS_PORT=443

# Optional: paths to a TLS keypair (see docs/deployment-setup.md). No domain
# was purchased for this deployment, but a free one (sslip.io — an IP
# address embedded in a hostname, e.g. 169-58-53-109.sslip.io, no signup)
# gets a REAL Let's Encrypt certificate via certbot — self-signed doesn't
# work here because the WhatsApp Cloud API webhook requires a publicly
# trusted cert (Meta rejects self-signed outright). Leave both unset for
# plain HTTP (local dev, scripts/verify-postgres.mjs).
# VPS_TLS_CERT_PATH="/etc/letsencrypt/live/<subdomain>.sslip.io/fullchain.pem"
# VPS_TLS_KEY_PATH="/etc/letsencrypt/live/<subdomain>.sslip.io/privkey.pem"

# requirements.md §6/§7: WhatsApp Cloud API (Meta) — see
# docs/deployment-setup.md's WhatsApp section for the full setup, including
# the one manual step (registering the webhook URL + verify token in the
# Meta App Dashboard) that only a human with dashboard access can do.
# PHONE_NUMBER_ID/ACCESS_TOKEN go in BOTH .envs — the local server needs
# them for the scheduled daily send, the VPS needs them to reply from the
# webhook. The next two (WEBHOOK_VERIFY_TOKEN, REPORT_RECIPIENT) are
# VPS-only — the local server never receives inbound messages.
# WHATSAPP_PHONE_NUMBER_ID="..."
# WHATSAPP_ACCESS_TOKEN="..."
# Arbitrary secret this deployment picks; Meta echoes it back on webhook
# registration so we can confirm the verification request actually came
# from Meta's config flow. Generate with e.g. `openssl rand -hex 20`.
# WHATSAPP_WEBHOOK_VERIFY_TOKEN="change-me"
# VPS-only: which WhatsApp number(s) the webhook will reply to — a security
# boundary, deliberately not read from synced AppSettings (see src/env.ts).
# Comma-separated for more than one, digits only per number, no +.
# Each number must also be added as a verified test recipient in the Meta
# App Dashboard (test-mode numbers only reply to their own allow-list) —
# that step has no API, only the dashboard.
# WHATSAPP_REPORT_RECIPIENT="923001234567,923341234567"
